(3 points) We can use a linked list to implement a stack. We assume that we use structure Node with two members to represent a node of the linked list. The member data stores the data, and the member next points to the next node in the linked list. Also we use a variable head to point to the first node of the linked list. head is initialized to NULL.

1. Pushing the value of a variable i into the stack can be implemented as follows.

   newHead = malloc(sizeof(Node));
   newHead->data = i;
   newHead->next = head;
   head = newHead;

2. Popping the top of the stack into a variable i can be implemented as follows.

   free(head);
   i = head->data;
   head = head->next;

3. To test if the stack is empty we can check if the head is a NULL pointer.

4. We can improve the push/pop efficiency of this stack by adding another pointer tail that points to the end of the linked list, so we can access the last node in the list in O(1) time.

5. We can improve the push/pop efficiency of this stack by adding another pointer member into every node, so it becomes a double linked list. That is, we can traverse in both directions in this linked list.

The following shows an array-based implementation of ADT Stack that stores non-duplicated integers. NOTE: The stack class has NO member function of data swapping!! All item switching or swapping operations must be implemented by yourself!

const int MAXSIZE = 20; // the maximal stack size

class Stack
{
public:
    // insert an integer into the stack
    int push(int data);
    // reverse the order of the integers in the stack
    void reverse();
    // rank the integers in the stack in ascending order
    void rank();
private:
    int items[MAXSIZE]; // the array of the stacked integers
    int top; // the index of the top item, the initial is -1
}

(a) (10 points) Write the Stack::push() function that inserts an integer into the stack. Note that the function returns -1 if either the stack is full or the input integer has already existed in the stack; otherwise, it returns 0.

(b) (10 points) Write the Stack::reverse() function that reverses the sequence of the stacked integers.

(c) (20 points) Write the Stack::rank() function that ranks the stacked integers in ascending order. In other words, the top is the smallest integer. You MUST employ the bubble sort algorithm to rank the data!!

